  "response": "The extremely long rendering time for each frame of the black hole in Interstellar was due to the complex and scientifically accurate simulation of gravitational lensing and light bending around a massive black hole. The visual effects team, led by Double Negative, worked closely with theoretical physicist Kip Thorne to create a mathematically precise representation of how light would actually behave near a supermassive black hole.\n\nThe rendering was complex because it had to accurately simulate:\n1. Gravitational lensing effects\n2. Light bending around the event horizon\n3. Relativistic light distortions\n4. Accurate visual representation of spacetime warping\n\nEach frame required massive computational power to calculate the complex physics of light movement and gravitational effects, resulting in the 120-hour (5-day) rendering time per individual frame. The goal was to create the most scientifically accurate black hole visualization ever seen in cinema, which necessitated extremely detailed and computationally intensive rendering processes.",
